<Author>BeenThereToo
<Content>Great Location and Very Accommodating We really liked just about every aspect of the Eliot Hotel. The location, the service, the restaurant, and the room.Everyone was very friendly when we checked in to our one bedroom suite. And we had a LOT of luggage including a big tandem stroller for our two toddlers. The doormen had a hell of time helping us with all our luggage. Unfortunately for them there are no ramps so they had to carry our (and everyone's) bags up 4 or 5 steps into the foyer and then down 4 or 5 more to the front desk and elevators. Very elegant foyer but if you ask me it's a design flaw!Anyway, the room was perfect for us because it faced the back alley which was quiet for the most part. (There was a recycling dumpster somewhere nearby that got a lot of business about 2am each night.) A friend stayed in a room facing Mass Ave and had problems sleeping due to all the noise and traffic. The room was very nicely appointed, a nice bed, good-sized bathroom, two tvs, a big desk and central air/heat. The only thing missing was a closet.The partition between the bedroom and the living room was a set of french doors. Very romantic but since we were there with our children it actually worked against us. The thin white curtains didn't keep much of our bedroom light out of the living room where the kids were sleeping on the pull-out sofa. We folded up the sofabed each morning so I was impressed that housekeeping actually opened the bed, straightened the sheets and made the bed and folded it back up again.The doormen probably wanted to kill us since we entered and exited the hotel 4 or 5 times per day for 5 days. Each time they smiled as the bent over and hefted the stroller with two sleeping toddlers up and down the stairs. They deserve a raise after putting up with us.The restaraunt, Clio, is one of Boston's best for dinner. And the breakfast buffet is reasonable for what you get-- $18 for a continental buffet with very nice servers. But if you want eggs, bacon, potatoes and toast with a coffee and juice, be prepared to shell out about $35.And lastly the location was great with a T stop (subway) across the street. Also the Prudential Center (mall), the Charles River, the Esplanade, and Newbury Street were all within 5 minutes. 
